   Prague, CZECH REPUBLIC, MAY 05-07, 2020},
Abstract = {With the currently vast volume of data available, several institutions,
   including the public sector, benefit from information, aiming to improve
   decision-making. Machine Learning enhances data-driven decision-making
   with its predictive power. In this work, our principal motivation was to
   apply Machine Learning to ameliorate fiscal audit planning for Sao
   Paulo's municipality. In this study, we predicted crimes against the
   service tax system of Sao Paulo using Machine Learning. Our methodology
   embraced the following steps: data extraction; data preparation;
   dimensionality reduction; model training and testing; model evaluation;
   model selection. Our experimental findings revealed that Sammon Mapping
   (SM) combined with Gradient Boosted Trees (GBT) outranked other
   state-of-the-art works, classifiers and dimensionality reduction
   techniques as regards classification performance. Our belief is that the
   ensemble of classifiers of GBT, combined with SM's ability to identify
   relevant dimensions in data, contributed to produce higher prediction
   scores. These scores enable Sao Paulo's tax administration to rank
   fiscal audits according to the highest probabilities of tax crime
   occurrence, leveraging tax revenue.},
